Abstract

Unlearning methods for recommender systems (RS) have emerged to address privacy issues and concerns about legal compliance. However, evolving user preferences and content licensing issues still remain unaddressed. This is particularly true in case of multi-modal recommender systems (MMRS), which aim to accommodate the growing influence of multi-modal information on user preferences. Previous unlearning methods for RS are inapplicable to MMRS due to incompatibility of multi-modal user-item behavior data graph with the matrix based representation of RS. Partitioning based methods degrade recommendation performance and incur significant overhead costs during aggregation. This paper introduces MMRecUN, a new framework for multi-modal recommendation unlearning, which, to the best of our knowledge, is the first attempt in this direction. Given the trained recommendation model and marked forget data, we devise Reverse Bayesian Personalized Ranking (BPR) objective to force the model to forget it. MMRecUN employs both reverse and forward BPR loss mechanisms to selectively attenuate the impact of interactions within the forget set while concurrently reinforcing the significance of interactions within the retain set. Our experiments demonstrate that MMRecUN outperforms baseline methods across various unlearning requests when evaluated on benchmark multi-modal recommender datasets. MMRecUN achieves recall performance improvements of up to 49.85%percent49.85\mathbf{49.85\%}bold_49.85 % compared to the baseline methods. It is up to 1.3Ã—\mathbf{1.3}\timesbold_1.3 Ã— faster than the Gold model, which is trained on retain data from scratch. MMRecUN offers advantages such as superior performance in removing target elements, preservation of performance for retained elements, and zero overhead costs in comparison to previous methods. Code will be released after review.

1 Introduction

Recommender systemsÂ [38]Â [18](RS), utilizing techniques such as collaborative filtering, content-based filtering, and neural networks, have transformed online experiences by offering personalized recommendations for diverse content types, including movies, music, products, news articles, etc. thus improving user engagement and satisfaction. As user preferences are getting influenced by multi-modal informationÂ [10], multimedia recommendation is gaining attention in recent timesÂ [48]Â [62]. Recent worksÂ [54]Â [31]Â [46]Â [45]Â [51] model user preferences based on both behavior information and item multi-modal information. With the rising demands for data privacy, regulations like GDPRÂ [42], CCPAÂ [15], and LGPDÂ [19] emphasize user rights towards data protection and â€œbe forgottenâ€. While user privacyÂ [59]Â [55] has been addressed through unlearning user-related data in RSÂ [4]Â [25]; the unlearning of item-related data in multi-modal recommender systems (MMRS) remains unexplored.

Motivation. We discuss some recent events and other probable scenarios where multi-modal recommender unlearning would be a great support:

Complex content licensing agreements: The recent decision by Universal Music Group (UMG)Â [21] to pull its library off from TikTok, silencing millions of user-created videos, requires TikTokâ€™s RS to adapt to the absence of UMG content. The 2020 lawsuitÂ [11] against Spotify by Wixen Music Publishing regarding songwritersâ€™ compensation may potentially influence the effectiveness of the underlying recommendation algorithm. The 2016 disputeÂ [24] between YouTube and Warner Music Group led to temporary content removal. So, there is a potential for conflict between existing models and evolving contractual obligations, underscoring the need for adaptable RS.

Legal compliance: The Algorithmic Accountability ActÂ [17] underscores the responsibility of companies to evaluate their machine learning systems for bias and discrimination. Current RS, however, often reinforce existing user preferences, perpetuating stereotypes and limiting diversity through filter bubbles and echo chambers Â [5]Â [29]. This necessitates systems to personalize effectively and promote fairness and exposure to diverse viewpoints.

Evolving user interests in different modalities: Consider a user who typically posts content related to fitness and healthy living. However, over time, she develops a new interest in travel photography and shares photos and stories from her recent trips to exotic locations. While the images and hashtags reflect passion for travel, the recommender system continues to prioritize fitness-related content in its recommendations. By analyzing both text and image modalities, the system can provide more relevant and personalized recommendations, enhancing the userâ€™s browsing experience.

Selective unlearning based on modalities: In the case of UMG removing its library from TikTok, the recommender system needs to adapt to the absence of UMG audio content while still considering other modalities like videos. In MMRS, both the graph structure and feature embeddings are tightly integrated. Unlearning interactions in one modality may have cascading effects on the representations and relationships within the entire graph.

Aiding selective transfer: With the growing concern for data privacy, cross-domain recommendation models face challenges in accessing domain-shareable user-item information across different platforms. Traditional assumptions of such models become impractical due to strict data privacy protection policiesÂ [32]. Sharing information across domains can be beneficial, but it can also lead to negative transfer. Imagine a movie recommendation system where the source domain is horror movies and the target domain is comedies. Sharing horror movie ratings might not be helpful for recommending comedies. Unlearning algorithms can be used to identify and remove irrelevant or misleading information from the source domain data before transferring it to the target domain.

Multi-modal recommendation unlearning that works for both user-related data and item-related data can be a promising response to these multifaceted challenges. By enabling systems to dynamically update their models and remove previously learned associations with unavailable or irrelevant content, unlearning holds the potential to enhance user privacy, ensure legal compliance, adapt to changing content licensing and evolve with user choices. It can also mitigate recommendation bias and data poisoning. Moreover, unlearning can reduce the GPU-hours carbon footprint that results from repeated retraining from scratch.

Background and Related Work. RS can be categorized into various types based on their underlying techniques. These include collaborative filtering (CF), matrix factorization (MF), content-based filtering (CBF), sequential recommender systems (SRS), graph convolutional network-based (GCN) and hybrids of these systems. While pioneering works have explored various unlearning approachesÂ [34], previous unlearning methods for RS using MF Â [30]Â [50]Â [33]Â [60], CF Â [28]Â [37], or SRSÂ [52] typically operate on behavior matrices. This approach makes them incompatible with multi-modal GCN-based RS which rely on bipartite graph representations. Even unlearning methods for uni-modal GCN-based RS, whether exact or approximate, face challenges in transitioning to multi-modal GCN-based systems due to the intricate integration of diverse modalitiesÂ [7]. Unlearning interactions within one modality can cascade through the entire graph, impacting its representations and relationships.Â Approximate unlearningÂ [53]Â [61]Â [26] entail computationally expensive operations, such as calculating the inverse of Hessian matrix for influence functions and the Fisher Information Matrix. Consequently, they are impractical for MMRS with large number of feature dimensions. Exact unlearningÂ [4]Â [25] methods adapt SISAÂ [1] to partitioning the dataset into shards. However, this approach disrupts the graph structure and leads to performance drops within each shard due to insufficient training data and poor data heterogeneityÂ [22]. Moreover, efforts to preserve data structure and aggregate performance across shards introduce significant overhead costs, impacting both training and inference procedures, with the burden increasing proportionally to the number of shardsÂ [35]. Further, when users that need to be forgotten come from multiple shards, it effectively falls back to retraining from scratch. Most importantly, their primary focus remains on user privacy through unlearning user-related data, overlooking the crucial need for unlearning item-related data to address evolving content licensing, legal compliance, or user preferences. These constraints underscore the need for tailored methodologies specifically designed for unlearning in MMRS. The supplementary material (AppendixÂ H) provides further insights into the challenges and other previous works Â [7]Â [56]Â [27]Â [3]Â [13]Â [49]Â [44].

Our contributions. The main contributions are summarized as follows:

  1. 1.

    We propose MMRecUN, a comprehensive framework for multi-modal recommendation unlearning. We define the problem of user and item unlearning in MMRS. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first attempt towards unlearning in MMRS.

  2. 2.

    Our work consider a variety of unlearning requests, such as single interaction removal, adjusting user preferences or eliminating bias based on multiple interaction removal, account deletion by removing all interactions of a user, and item removal by eliminating all interactions related to an item. Particularly, we clearly define three metrics for effectively measuring unlearning in MMRS. The paper also introduces and employs, item-centric metrics for evaluating item-unlearning along with user-centric metrics. The previous unlearning methods only used user-centric metrics.

  3. 3.

    The experiments demonstrate that MMRecUN outperforms the baselines across various unlearning requests. It achieves recall performance improvements of up to 49.85%percent49.85\mathbf{49.85\%}bold_49.85 % compared to the baseline methods. It is up to 1.3Ã—\mathbf{1.3}\timesbold_1.3 Ã— faster than the Gold model, which is trained on retain data from scratch.Additionally, MMRecUN offers advantages such as enhanced efficiency, superior performance in removing target elements, preservation of performance for retained elements, and minimal overhead costs.

Reverse Bayesian Personalized Ranking Objective. To achieve the objectives of unlearning in recommender systems, MMRecUN employs a reverse objective inspired by the concept of amnesiac unlearningÂ [16]. This approach suggests selectively undoing the learning steps associated with a forget set ğ’Ÿfsubscriptğ’Ÿğ‘“\mathcal{D}_{f}caligraphic_D start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, essentially removing the parameter updates related to forgotten data points and thus minimizing the predicted probability to a sufficiently small value. This works well for traditional machine learning tasks like image classification. Extending it to our context of recommender systems, the reverse objective of user uğ‘¢uitalic_u for her marked interactions is: minimize the predicted score of marked interactions relative to items with which she did not interact.

The Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergenceÂ [23, 14, 41] is difficult to implement in RS because the typical user-item interaction data are not inherently probabilistic but based on scores or ratings. Further, KL Divergence can be undefined when the target distribution has zero probability for an event that the input distribution considers likely, which can be problematic in sparse and high-dimensional recommendation datasets. Therefore, we propose BPR (Bayesian Personalized Ranking) divergence as an alternative which directly measures the difference between the predicted scores of user-item interactions from different model states using mean squared error, which aligns well with the numerical nature of recommendation scores.

4 Experiments and Results

4.1 Experiment Settings

Datasets and baselines. We use three distinct categories within the Amazon datasetÂ [20] that are used to benchmark MMRS (see Appendix E). The model trained on the retain set (named as the Gold model) from scratch is used as baseline. We prepare another baseline by re-purposing the image classification unlearningÂ AmUnÂ [16] for multi-model recommender unlearning.

Previous RS unlearning methods using matrix factorization, collaborative filtering, or sequential recommendation systems operate on behavior matrices, making them incompatible with graph-based architectures. The code for approximate methods Rrl, Ifru, and Scif is unavailable. Exact methods, RecEraser and UltraRE, require partitioning, which is challenging due to the need for specialized handling of each modality and ensuring coherence during aggregation, adding complexity outside the scope of this work.

Evaluation metrics To evaluate a given recommendation model Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ), we need model predictions: the ranked list of user-item pairs; the ground truth: user-item interactions ğ’´ğ’´\mathcal{Y}caligraphic_Y; and, Kğ¾Kitalic_K: the number of the top recommendations to consider. To capture a variety of aspects of performance, we use predictive metrics, that reflect the â€œcorrectness", how well Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ) finds relevant items such as Recall at K and Precision at K; and ranking metrics, that reflect the ranking quality, how well Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ) can sort the items from more relevant to less relevant. NDCG considers both the relevance and the position of items in the ranked list. MAP measures the average Precision across different Recall levels for a ranked list.

Settings and Hyper-parameters All the experiments are performed on 4444x NVIDIA RTX2080 (32323232GB). We use the identical settings as in the case of Mgcn for training the original recommender model Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ). The data interaction history of each user is split 8:1:1:81:18:1:18 : 1 : 1 for training, validation and testing. The training set is used to create retain set and forget set. We initialize the embedding with Xavier initialization of dimension 64646464, set the regularization coefficient to Î»Ï†=10âˆ’4subscriptğœ†ğœ‘superscript104\lambda_{\varphi}=10^{-4}italic_Î» start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_Ï† end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 10 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT - 4 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, and the batch size to B=2048ğµ2048B=2048italic_B = 2048. For the self-supervised task, we set the temperature to 0.20.20.20.2. For convergence, the early stopping and total epochs are fixed at 20202020 and 1000100010001000, respectively. We use Recall@20 on the validation data as the training-stopping indicator following [58]. We conducted experiments five times using different seed values and report the standard deviation values for item unlearning in TableÂ 3. For the other types of unlearning, the standard deviation values were found to be negligible and are therefore omitted.

4.2 Results

We conduct experiments to assess the unlearning performance of MMRecUN in the four aspects. First, we compare recall, precision, NDCG and MAP metrics on forget set. Values closer to the Gold model signify better Unlearning Specificity. Second, we compare the metrics on test set. Values closer to the Gold model signify better Retention Fidelity. Third, we compare the metrics on validation set. Values closer to the Gold model signify better Unlearning Generalizability. Finally, we compare the time duration required for unlearning to compare efficiency.

User-centric metrics measure the relevance from userâ€™s perspective i.e., whether the relevant items (the user likes or interacts with) are present in the top Kğ¾Kitalic_K recommendations. Users typically expect to see a small number of recommendations (e.g., 5555 or 10101010), hence we take K=5,10,20,50ğ¾5102050K=5,10,20,50italic_K = 5 , 10 , 20 , 50 to assess how well the system can provide personalized and focused recommendations. Larger values of Kğ¾Kitalic_K, such as 20202020 or 50505050, are useful for evaluating the systemâ€™s ability to cover a wider range of user preferences or measure performance in suggesting diverse options and catering to different user tastes. These metrics primarily focus on user satisfaction and do not capture the effectiveness of forgetting specific items. Hence, for item-unlearning, we introduce several item-centric metrics as well.

Item-centric metrics measure the relevance of the recommended items themselves i.e., how well the recommended items meet unlearning criteria, regardless of which users receive them. We take K=500,1000,1500ğ¾50010001500K=500,1000,1500italic_K = 500 , 1000 , 1500 to ensure that all items in the forget set ğ’Ÿfsubscriptğ’Ÿğ‘“\mathcal{D}_{f}caligraphic_D start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_f end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are considered for evaluating performance.

User Unlearning. TableÂ 2 presents the results of unlearning 5%percent55\%5 % users. The Gold model, which has never seen the forget set, falls in performance on this set as expected. However, it retains good performance on the test and validation sets. On the validation set, MMRecUN consistently achieves better recall scores, outperforming AmUn by 29.6%percent29.629.6\%29.6 %, 49.85%percent49.8549.85\%49.85 %, and 34.75%percent34.7534.75\%34.75 % on the three datasets (baby, sports, and clothing, respectively), showcasing best unlearning generalizability. Furthermore, on the test set, MMRecUN maintains closest recall scores, surpassing AmUn by 26.69%percent26.6926.69\%26.69 %, 46.93%percent46.9346.93\%46.93 %, and 36.13%percent36.1336.13\%36.13 %, demonstrating best retention fidelity. On the forget set, MMRecUN achieves better recall scores, outperforming AmUn by 3.8%percent3.83.8\%3.8 % and 43.75%percent43.7543.75\%43.75 % on two datasets and slightly falling back by 2.08%percent2.082.08\%2.08 % on the clothing dataset, indicating high unlearning specificity. Similar trends follow for other metrics.

We evaluate the impact of Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± on the balance between adaptation and reform in the unlearning process, experimenting with Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± values from 0.0010.0010.0010.001 to 0.90.90.90.9 (TableÂ 5). As Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± increases (0.30.30.30.3-0.90.90.90.9), the model emphasizes more on the reform loss, needing more epochs to forget and adversely affecting retain set recall. Extremely low Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± values (<0.01absent0.01<0.01< 0.01) hinder effective forgetting, also increasing epochs needed and negatively impacting retain set. The optimal Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± depends on the specific taskâ€™s forgetting severity and time constraints: higher Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± may ensure stronger forgetting with minor recall loss, while lower Î±ğ›¼\alphaitalic_Î± enables faster convergence. 5 Conclusion

We introduce MMRecUN, a new framework for unlearning in MMRS. While previous methods are incompatible with the complex multi-modal data structures of MMRS, MMRecUN balances the removal of specified interactions with maintaining the recommendation modelâ€™s performance on retained interactions. Using a Reverse Bayesian Personalized Ranking (BPR) objective, MMRecUN attenuates the impact of interactions marked for forgetting while reinforcing the importance of retained interactions. Our experimental results validate the effectiveness of MMRecUN, demonstrating substantial improvements unlearning specificity, retention fidelity, generalizability and efficiency.

B.2 Unlearning with Traditional Workflow: Retraining

To cater to demands for privacy, legal compliance, and evolving user preferences and content licensing grow, the recommender model Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ) has to adapt dynamically. Thus, either of the four unlearning requests can come up.

  1. 1.

    Single interaction removal (privacy needs): This request involves removing a single interaction between a user and an item from the model. It addresses privacy concerns by allowing users to delete specific interactions they no longer want associated with their profile. For example, if a user wants to remove a movie they watched from their viewing history for privacy reasons, the system would unlearn this interaction.

  2. 2.

    Multiple interaction removal (user preference adjustment, bias elimination): In this request, multiple interactions of the same user with different items or multiple interactions of the same item across many users are removed. It aims to adjust user preferences, eliminate bias, and mitigate shilling attacksÂ [12]Â [39] by updating the model based on the removal of these interactions. Shilling attacks involve artificially inflating the ratings or interactions of certain items to manipulate recommendations, and this removal process helps counteract such malicious behavior.

  3. 3.

    Removal of all interactions of a user for account deletion (privacy laws): This request involves removing all interactions associated with a specific user from the model, effectively deleting their entire profile and history from the system to comply with privacy regulations.

  4. 4.

    Removal of all interactions related to an item (evolving license): In this request, all interactions related to a particular item are removed from the model. It addresses evolving content licensing agreements by adapting the model to the absence or unavailability of certain items. For instance, if a music label withdraws its catalog from the platform, the system would unlearn all interactions associated with songs from that label to comply with the licensing changes.

After receiving the requests, the recommendation system must execute two processes. The first process involves removing data from the database by nullifying interaction data in the interaction matrix, yu,i=0subscriptğ‘¦ğ‘¢ğ‘–0y_{u,i}=0italic_y start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_u , italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, âˆ€yu,iâˆˆğ’´u+for-allsubscriptğ‘¦ğ‘¢ğ‘–superscriptsubscriptğ’´ğ‘¢\forall y_{u,i}\in\mathcal{Y}_{u}^{+}âˆ€ italic_y start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_u , italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT âˆˆ caligraphic_Y start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_u end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. B.3 Proposed MMRecUN Workflow for Unlearning

As discussed in SectionÂ G, retraining the recommendation model from scratch poses computational inefficiencies due to the large volume of interactions and the size of the model itself. This challenge is further exacerbated when multiple unlearning requests occur sequentially over time. Hence, we advocate for unlearning the initially trained model Mâ¢(â‹…,Ï†)ğ‘€â‹…ğœ‘M(\cdot,\varphi)italic_M ( â‹… , italic_Ï† ) using MMRecUN.

Appendix F Discussion

Limitations: First, the method primarily focuses on user-item interactions without explicitly considering the temporal dynamics of interactions, which may be important in certain applications. Second, our approach assumes that the data to be forgotten is clearly identifiable, which might not always be the case in zero-shot unlearning scenarios.

Impact: MMRecUN offers significant positive societal impacts, such as enhanced privacy, increased user trust, ethical data handling, and improved recommendation quality by enabling users to control their data and align with privacy regulations like GDPR. However, it also presents potential negative impacts, including the risk of misuse for manipulation, loss of valuable insights, increased computational costs, unintended consequences on model behavior. For example, malicious actors might repeatedly request the unlearning of certain interactions to bias the system in a way that benefits them.

Future research can extend MMRecUN to handle more complex types of multi-modal data . Another promising direction is to investigate automated methods for identifying data to be forgotten, improving the practicality and robustness of unlearning in MMRS.

Appendix G Challenges in Multi-modal Recommendation Unlearning

Previous methods cannot be directly applied to multi-modal GCN-based recommender systems due to the following challenges.

Divergence in Model Representations: Multi-modal GCN models, incorporate heterogeneous user-item image, text and behavior information into a unified graph, contrasting with the matrices, latent factors, feature representations, and temporal sequences used in traditional recommender systems like CF, MF, CBF, and SRS, respectively. Consequently, transferring unlearning mechanisms is not as straight-forward.

Incompatibility with Uni-modal Approaches: Uni-modal recommender systems, even those based on GCNs, fail to directly apply to multi-modal GCN-based systems due to the inherent complexities of integrating diverse modalitiesÂ [7]. Both the graph structure and feature embeddings are tightly integrated, making it non-trivial to modify one component without affecting the other. Unlearning interactions in one modality may have cascading effects on the representations and relationships within the entire graph.

Expensive operations: The computational overhead associated with computing the Hessian matrix or adjusting the interaction matrix or computing the inverse of Hessian for influence function or Fisher Information Matrix may become prohibitive as the size of the dataset or the number of interactions increases, making some of the methods less practical for large-scale recommender systems.

Ill-effects of sharding: Partitioning data breaks the graph structure. Partitioning based on items restricts the systemâ€™s ability to recommend items across different partitions to users, and partitioning based on users leads to insufficient training data and poor data heterogeneityÂ [22]. This causes a significant drop (âˆ¼30%similar-toabsentpercent30\sim 30\%âˆ¼ 30 %) in performanceÂ [53]. This adds unlearning overhead of extra computational cost and time at the time of training . When items that need to be forgotten come from multiple shards, the worst case efficiency falls to the level of retraining from scratch. The modelâ€™s initial setup, partitioned based on users during training, poses a challenge to implementing item-related data unlearning, as it cannot be readily reconfigured to partition data based on items. Item-related data unlearning concurrently with user-related data unlearning is not possible.

Burden of aggregation: Additional steps to aggregate performance across shards introduce significant overhead costs, with the burden increasing proportionally to the number of shardsÂ [35]. This adds unlearning overhead of extra computational cost and time at the time of inference. The partition-aggregation framework is prohibitive for the models which have already been trained.

These constraints underscore the need for tailored methodologies specifically designed for unlearning in multi-modal recommender systems.

Appendix H Related Work

Recommender Systems. Recommender systems can be categorized into various types based on their underlying techniques. These include collaborative filtering (CF), matrix factorization (MF), content-based filtering (CBF), sequential recommender systems (SRS), graph convolutional network-based (GCN) and hybrids of these systems. Recent advancements have seen a surge in research on multi-modal recommender systems Â [51]Â [45]Â [46]Â [31], which leverage multiple modalities such as text, images, and videos to enhance recommendation accuracy and user satisfaction. The current state-of-the-art MgcnÂ [54], a GCN model, leverages multiple views to separate modality features and behavior features, enhancing feature discriminability, and considers the relative importance of different modalities for improved user preference modeling.

Machine Unlearning. In recent years, significant advancements have been made in the field of machine unlearningÂ [2]Â [1] across various domains such as image classificationÂ [40]Â [9]Â [8], regressionÂ [41], federated learningÂ [47], graph learningÂ [6]Â [43], and more. Exact unlearningÂ [1] aims to completely remove the influence of specific data points from the model through algorithmic-level retraining. The advantage is the model will behave as if the unlearned data had never been seen. While providing strong guarantees of removal, exact unlearning usually demands extensive computational resources and is primarily suitable for simpler models.Â Approximate unlearning focuses on efficiently minimizing the influence of target data points through limited parameter-level updates to the model. While not removing influence entirely, approximate unlearning significantly reduces computational and time costs. It enables practical unlearning applications even for large-scale and complex machine learning models, where exact retraining is infeasible.

Multi-modal Machine Unlearning. In MmulÂ [7], unlearning is accomplished by minimizing the dissimilarity between the multi-modal representations of deleted pairs and randomly drawn unassociated pairs. At the same time, uni-modal and multi-modal knowledge is preserved by minimizing the difference between the uni-modal and multi-modal representations produced by the unlearned model and the original model.

Recommendation Unlearning. Various methods for unlearning have been explored in different types of recommender systems as summarized in TableÂ 10. For collaborative filtering, CabooseÂ [37] incrementally adjusts the user-item matrices and re-calculates similarities only for affected entries to reflect the removal of a specific interaction. This approach avoids complete re-computation, effectively conserving computational resources. LaserÂ [28] partitions users according to collaborative embedding and trains them sequentially with curriculum learning.

For matrix factorization, IMCorrectÂ [30] adjusts the interaction matrix by weakening item pairsâ€™ similarity if they had high similarity due to similar interaction patterns in the removed interactions, reflecting the unlearned recommendations. In another workCmumfÂ [60], performs a closed-form unlearning update based on the total Hessian-based Newton step, allowing for the efficient removal of the influence of specific rows or columns from the trained MF factors. ALSÂ [50] modifies the intermediate confidence matrix used in Alternating Least Squares to achieve fast forgetting. AltEraserÂ [33] unlearns via alternating optimization in Alternating Least squares.

For sequential recommender systems, DyRandÂ [52] leverages label noise injection to make random predictions for sequences to be unlearned. Among uni-modal GCN-based systems, exact unlearning has been investigated by RecEraserÂ [4]. It partitions training set into shards, train sub-models and employs attention-based adaptive aggregation strategies to combine performance of shards. For unlearning, one of the sub-models whose shard contains the interaction to be unlearned and the aggregation part needs to be retrained. UltraREÂ [25] improves partitioning by optimal balanced clustering and aggregation by logistic regression.

Among uni-modal GCN-based systems, approximate unlearning has been explored by IfruÂ [61] which updates the model based on influence of data to be unlearned. ScifÂ [26] improves by selectively updating user embeddings based on their collaborative influence. RrlÂ [53] uses reverse BPR loss to unlearn and Fisher Information Matrix to preserve remaining user-item interactions. Though, computing the inverse of Hessian for influence function and Fisher Information Matrix are computationally expensive operations.
